@article{Korte2005a,
abstract = {Two hundred sixty-four delta(18)O and delta(13)C values of Permian articulate brachiopod shells were analyzed and 81 of these values were characterized as well preserved and biostratigraphically well defined. These were then utilized for construction of baseline oxygen and carbon isotope curves for the Permian interval. In addition, 21 delta(13)C whole rock values are reported for the Wordian and Capitanian. The early Permian, Asselian to Artinskian, times are characterized by similar to 2.5 parts per thousand decrease in oxygen isotope values, from similar to-0.7 parts per thousand to -3.3 parts per thousand (V-PDB). This is attributed to a similar to 4-7 degrees C increase in temperature in the Southern Urals, concomitant with the retreat of the Permo-Carboniferous ice sheets and return of the O-18-depleted melt water into the oceans. The Late Permian samples from Iran (Jolfa at Kuh-e-Ali-Bashi) and China (Meishan) yield delta(18)O values, and presumably temperatures, similar to those that followed the termination of the large-scale glaciation in the Lower Permian. In between, the upper Kungurian to Capitanian samples from the Delaware Basin (Guadalupe Mountains) are enriched in O-18, at -1.5 parts per thousand to -3 parts per thousand. We have no definitive explanation for these data, but tentatively suggest that the "anomaly" can potentially be a result of evaporative enrichment of seawater in O-18, due to intracratonic, and setting of the basin. The O-18-enriched nature of the Zechstein samples (-1.2 parts per thousand to +2.5 parts per thousand), on the other hand, is in all probability a reflection of the high evaporation rates in the Zechstein sea. The Permian interval is characterized by a relatively constant delta(13)C, at about 4 parts per thousand. The exceptions are again the brachiopods from the Delaware Basin (Guadalupe Mountains), which show similar to 1.6 parts per thousand increase in the Guadalupian, to values of up to 5.9 parts per thousand in the Wordian. A tentative explanation, as in the case of oxygen, is based on the proposition that the semi-enclosed Delaware Basin was likely stratified, with sequestration of the C-13-depleted carbon to the deeper water layers and a complementary C-13 enrichment in the upper oxygenated layer. The coeval open ocean water DIC may have been similar to that of the remainder of the Permian interval, at similar to 4 parts per thousand, as indicated by whole rock carbonate samples from Oman, Sicily, and Iran. In the latest Permian, the trend mimics the well-known delta(13)C drop at the Permian/Triassic boundary. (c) 2005 Elsevier B.V. All rights reserved.},
